  <p>An important note on the upper end: levels above 100 ng/mL may be associated with toxicity — primarily through hypercalcemia and calcification of soft tissues. Vitamin D toxicity from supplementation is rare but real at very high doses. The 50–80 ng/mL range reflects both the evidence for benefit and a meaningful safety margin below concerning levels.</p>

  <p>Research by Garland et al. analyzing pooled data from multiple studies found that serum 25(OH)D levels of 40–60 ng/mL were associated with approximately 50% lower risk of breast cancer compared to levels below 20 ng/mL. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17368188/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2</a></sup></p>
